# Chapter 3 — Song of the Lost and Forgotten (Taklamakan, China & Gandhara, India)

*Keeper-facing summary of Chapter 3 of The Children of Fear. Structure lives in
the sibling `.arc`, stat blocks in the `.actor`, campaign lore in
`children-of-fear-0.4-campaign-overview.lore`. Consult your copy of the campaign
for full text, read-aloud passages, and handouts. This is one of the three
any-order "Gathering" chapters (see the campaign `FLOW`).*

## Role in the campaign

One of the three middle chapters the party may attempt in any order after the
lama's charge in Chapter 2. Its component objective is to recover the **seven
ritual offering (alms) bowls** from an ancient holy site in Gandhara — needed for
the ritual against the King of Fear. Getting there means crossing the deadly
Taklamakan and the mountains into British India, so the chapter is heavily a
travel-and-survival leg braided with a Mythos infestation and a retrieval.

## Part One — The Land of Death (the Taklamakan)

A desert crossing with a **route choice** the players make:
- **The Northern Route** — out via the Jade Gate toward Turfan and the northern
  oasis chain ("High and Dry").
- **The Southern Route** — the alternate arm of the Tarim Basin.
Each route provides its own encounters (Travel-by-Map). A recurring thread —
**"A Thorn in Their Side"** — is an archaeologist who has *awoken something* in
buried ruins: several depicted figures in newly opened rooms have become restless
and **incarnate**, a Mythos manifestation that stalks the region.

## Part Two — Through the Mountains

The expedition climbs from the Tarim Basin over the mountain passes (the tangle of
ranges that vexed 19th-century geographers) down into **Gandhara** — the ancient
Buddhist kingdom in the Northwest Frontier (modern Pakistan/northern India). A
punishing high-altitude leg with its own hazards.

## Part Three — Still Waters (Gandhara / Chakdara)

**Set Up — Smoke and Mirrors.** The party searches an ancient holy site for the
**seven ritual offering bowls** — and finds them **missing**. The chapter becomes
a hunt to recover them.

**Start — Reflections.** However they arrive, the investigators reach a small
village near **Chakdara**, overlooked by a British fort and picket — so the
British colonial authorities are a complicating presence (a retrieval that could
"land them in hot water," as the overview warns).

**The bowls and the pisachas.** The offering bowls have been taken by **pisachas**
(flesh-eating Hindu demons); the investigators can catch them in the act of
stealing/handling the bowls or track them down. **The River of Life** and the
site's guardians/holy figures factor into recovering the set.

**Moving On.** With the seven bowls recovered, this Gathering component is
complete and the party can turn to the next (Ch4 / Ch5) or, once all three are
done, to the climax.

## Key NPCs & threats

- **The rogue archaeologist** — whose meddling awoke the incarnate ruin-images
  ("A Thorn in Their Side").
- **Pisachas** — the demon thieves of the offering bowls; the chapter's principal
  Mythos antagonists. (Stat blocks in the `.actor`.)
- **British fort garrison at Chakdara** — colonial authority to navigate.
- **The lama / the Tokabhaya** — the quest-giver's charge frames the objective;
  the antagonists' interest continues.

## Clues & handouts (as information)

- **Song 1 / Song 3 / Song 5** — the chapter's handouts (prophecy/verse
  fragments, e.g. the sandstorm-and-"Ghoul-infested"-desert warning, and route/
  lore aids the investigators can acquire).
- Regional *What Your Investigator Knows* handouts (the Tarim Basin; the
  Northwest Frontier; India/Gandhara) — the characters' baseline knowledge of the
  legs they traverse.

## Keeper guidance

- Let the players own the Northern-vs-Southern route decision; each is a distinct
  desert gauntlet.
- Play Chakdara's British garrison as friction for an unsanctioned retrieval, not
  merely set dressing.
- This chapter is self-contained enough to slot before or after Chapters 4 and 5;
  keep the lama's overall goal (the ritual components) as the throughline.

## Transition

Recovering the seven bowls checks off one of the three Gathering objectives. The
party proceeds to another middle chapter (Old Bones / Feast and Famine) or, when
all three are complete, into the Climax (Chapter 6, *Liberation*).
